Photo by Sticker it on UnsplashBecause copying the same component into six folders is not a design system
There is something worse than bad code: a codebase filled with duplicated spaghetti code that nobody understands, nobody wants to touch, and everybody insists is “temporary.”
You know the kind.
components/
├── UserModal.tsx
├── AdminUserModal.tsx
├── NewUserModal.tsx
├── UpdatedUserModal.tsx
├── UserModalFinal.tsx
└── UserModalFinalV2_REAL.tsxAt that point, you do not have reusable components. You have a digital landfill with TypeScript support.
In this article, we will build truly reusable React components by focusing on a few practical principles:

• Single responsibility

• Prop-driven extensibility

• Composition over configuration

• Flat, intentional APIs

• Flexible styling without chaos

• Responsive behavior by default
These are guidelines, not commandments carved into a stone tablet by the React core team. Use judgment. The goal is not to create the most abstract component possible. The goal is to create components that are useful, predictable, and difficult to misuse.

1. Follow the Single Responsibility Principle
You have probably heard that a reusable component is simply a component that can be shared.
That definition is technically correct in the same way that reheated gas-station sushi is technically food.
A component becomes truly reusable when it has one clear responsibility and performs that responsibility exceptionally well.
Look at mature libraries such as MUI, Bootstrap, and Lodash. Their most useful building blocks tend to be small and focused:

• A button triggers an action.

• A modal displays content above the current interface.

• A chip communicates a compact status.

• A utility function transforms one type of value.
Each piece behaves like a LEGO brick. It has a clear purpose, a predictable interface, and enough versatility to work in many different structures.
Press enter or click to view image in full size

Photo by Can Eğridere on UnsplashIt does not try to become the entire LEGO castle.
The wrong approach
This component displays a user, manages editing, performs an API request, displays notifications, and probably files the user’s taxes.
type UserCardProps = {
userId: string;
};export function UserCard({ userId }: UserCardProps) {
const [user, setUser] = useState<User | null>(null);
const [isEditing, setIsEditing] = useState(false);
useEffect(() => {
fetch(`/api/users/${userId}`)
.then((response) => response.json())
.then(setUser);
}, [userId]);
const handleSave = async () => {
await fetch(`/api/users/${userId}`, {
method: "PUT",
body: JSON.stringify(user),
});
alert("User saved!");
setIsEditing(false);
};
if (!user) {
return <div>Loading...</div>;
}
return (
<div>
<img src={user.avatarUrl} alt={user.name} />
{isEditing ? (
<input
value={user.name}
onChange={(event) =>
setUser({
...user,
name: event.target.value,
})
}
/>
) : (
<h2>{user.name}</h2>
)}
<button onClick={() => setIsEditing(true)}>Edit</button>
<button onClick={handleSave}>Save</button>
</div>
);
}
This component is tightly coupled to:

• A specific API endpoint

• A specific data structure

• Editing behavior

• Loading behavior

• Notification behavior

• Persistence logic
Reusing it somewhere else means bringing its entire extended family with it.
A better approach
Keep the visual component focused on rendering.
export type UserCardProps = {
name: string;
avatarUrl?: string;
subtitle?: string;
actions?: React.ReactNode;
};
export function UserCard({
name,
avatarUrl,
subtitle,
actions,
}: UserCardProps) {
return (
<article>
{avatarUrl && <img src={avatarUrl} alt="" />}
<div>
<h2>{name}</h2>
{subtitle && <p>{subtitle}</p>}
</div>
{actions && <div>{actions}</div>}
</article>
);
}The parent decides where the data comes from and what actions are available.
<UserCard
name={user.name}
avatarUrl={user.avatarUrl}
subtitle={user.jobTitle}
actions={
<button onClick={() => openEditor(user.id)}>
Edit user
</button>
}
/>The component does one thing: it displays user information.
It does not know whether the user came from REST, GraphQL, Supabase, local storage, or an Excel spreadsheet maintained by someone named Greg.
That separation is what makes it reusable.

2. Use Prop-Driven Extensibility
First, let us clear up a common misunderstanding:
Prop drilling and prop spreading are not the same thing.
Prop drilling is passing data through multiple components that do not need it just to reach a deeply nested component.
Prop spreading is forwarding a group of props to another element:
<button {...buttonProps} />They are not enemies, friends, or even coworkers. They are completely different concepts.
A reusable component should expose the capabilities of the element it wraps whenever doing so is safe and useful.
The wrong approach
type PrimaryButtonProps = {
label: string;
onClick: () => void;
};export function PrimaryButton({
label,
onClick,
}: PrimaryButtonProps) {
return <button onClick={onClick}>{label}</button>;
}
This works until someone needs:

• disabled

• aria-label

• type="submit"

• onFocus

• data-testid

• Keyboard events

• A tooltip

• A custom class name
The component author then adds one prop at a time until the type definition looks like a CVS receipt.
A better approach
Extend the native element’s props.
import type {
ButtonHTMLAttributes,
ReactNode,
} from "react";export type PrimaryButtonProps =
ButtonHTMLAttributes<HTMLButtonElement> & {
children: ReactNode;
};
export function PrimaryButton({
children,
type = "button",
...buttonProps
}: PrimaryButtonProps) {
return (
<button type={type} {...buttonProps}>
{children}
</button>
);
}
Now developers can use the button like a normal HTML button:
<PrimaryButton
type="submit"
disabled={isSaving}
aria-label="Save customer"
onClick={handleSave}
>
Save
</PrimaryButton>The component provides a useful default while preserving the native element’s capabilities.
Do not spread props blindly
The spread operator is useful, but it is not holy water. Do not sprinkle it everywhere and assume the architecture is now clean.
Be intentional about where the remaining props are applied.
export function SearchField({
label,
...inputProps
}: SearchFieldProps) {
return (
<label>
<span>{label}</span>
<input {...inputProps} />
</label>
);
}This makes sense because the additional props clearly belong to the input.
This is less clear:
export function MysteryComponent(props: Record<string, unknown>) {
return <div {...props} />;
}That is not flexibility. That is surrender.
Prop order matters
Consider this:
<button disabled={isLoading} {...buttonProps}>
Save
</button>A caller can override disabled because the spread comes last.
By contrast:
<button {...buttonProps} disabled={isLoading}>
Save
</button>The internal value wins.
Use the order intentionally:

• Put the spread last when callers should be allowed to override defaults.

• Put required internal behavior last when it must not be overridden.

3. Prefer Composition Over Configuration
One of the fastest ways to destroy a reusable component is to give it 47 Boolean props.
<DashboardCard
showTitle
showImage
showFooter
showActions
isCompact
isPremium
isAdmin
isExpandable
hasBorder
useNewDesign
useNewNewDesign
/>At this point, the component is not reusable. It is a hostage negotiation.
These “god components” try to support every possible design through configuration flags. The result is usually a giant collection of conditional statements that nobody can safely modify.
The LEGO horse principle
Imagine a LEGO horse.
The horse should not care whether you place a knight, queen, barrel, astronaut, or suspiciously confident monkey on top of it.
Its responsibility is to be a horse.
Likewise, a reusable component should often accept content through composition instead of trying to understand every possible type of content.
In React, that usually means using children and named slots.
The wrong approach
type PanelProps = {
title: string;
description: string;
buttonLabel?: string;
showIcon?: boolean;
iconName?: "warning" | "success" | "info";
showFooter?: boolean;
footerText?: string;
};This API assumes that every future panel will follow one exact structure.
The moment the design team adds a second button, an avatar, a dropdown, or a tiny animated llama, the component needs another prop.
A better approach
import type { ReactNode } from "react";export type PanelProps = {
header?: ReactNode;
children: ReactNode;
footer?: ReactNode;
};
export function Panel({
header,
children,
footer,
}: PanelProps) {
return (
<section>
{header && <header>{header}</header>}
<div>{children}</div>
{footer && <footer>{footer}</footer>}
</section>
);
}
Now the parent controls the content:
<Panel
header={
<div>
<h2>Server status</h2>
<StatusChip status="running" />
</div>
}
footer={
<button onClick={viewDetails}>
View details
</button>
}
>
<p>All systems are operating normally.</p>
</Panel>The structure remains consistent, but the content stays flexible.
That is composition.

4. Build a Reusable Modal
A modal is an excellent example because teams love creating one modal per feature until the bundle contains enough dialogs to launch a small operating system.
Here is a reusable modal built with MUI and TypeScript.
import type { ReactNode } from "react";
import {
Dialog,
DialogActions,
DialogContent,
DialogTitle,
} from "@mui/material";
import type { DialogProps } from "@mui/material/Dialog";export type AppModalProps = Omit<
DialogProps,
"open" | "onClose" | "children" | "title"
> & {
open: boolean;
onClose: () => void;
title?: ReactNode;
children: ReactNode;
actions?: ReactNode;
};
export function AppModal({
open,
onClose,
title,
children,
actions,
maxWidth = "sm",
fullWidth = true,
...dialogProps
}: AppModalProps) {
return (
<Dialog
{...dialogProps}
open={open}
onClose={onClose}
maxWidth={maxWidth}
fullWidth={fullWidth}
>
{title && <DialogTitle>{title}</DialogTitle>}
<DialogContent>{children}</DialogContent>
{actions && (
<DialogActions>{actions}</DialogActions>
)}
</Dialog>
);
}
The component handles the modal structure but does not decide what the modal is for.
Confirmation modal
<AppModal
open={isDeleteModalOpen}
onClose={closeDeleteModal}
title="Delete customer?"
actions={
<>
<Button onClick={closeDeleteModal}>
Cancel
</Button>
<Button
color="error"
onClick={deleteCustomer}
>
Delete
</Button>
</>
}
>
This action cannot be undone.
</AppModal>Form modal
<AppModal
open={isEditorOpen}
onClose={closeEditor}
title="Edit customer"
maxWidth="md"
actions={
<Button type="submit" form="customer-form">
Save
</Button>
}
>
<CustomerForm id="customer-form" />
</AppModal>Same modal. Different responsibility provided by the parent.
The reusable component owns:

• Dialog structure

• Sizing defaults

• Content areas

• Shared behavior
The parent owns:

• Business logic

• Form state

• API calls

• Button behavior

• Domain-specific content
Nobody needs to create DeleteCustomerModalFinal2.tsx.
Nature is healing.

5. Build a Reusable Status Chip
Suppose the product uses three common machine statuses:

• running

• off

• stopped
We want these statuses to map to semantic visual tones:

• running → success

• off → neutral

• stopped → danger
However, the displayed label should remain customizable.
For example, a dangerous status might display “Heating” instead of “Stopped.”
import { Chip } from "@mui/material";
import type { ChipProps } from "@mui/material/Chip";
export type Status =
| "running"
| "off"
| "stopped";
export type StatusTone =
| "success"
| "neutral"
| "danger";const defaultLabels: Record<Status, string> = {
running: "Running",
off: "Off",
stopped: "Stopped",
};
const defaultTones: Record<Status, StatusTone> = {
running: "success",
off: "neutral",
stopped: "danger",
};
const muiColors: Record<
StatusTone,
NonNullable<ChipProps["color"]>
> = {
success: "success",
neutral: "default",
danger: "error",
};
export type StatusChipProps = Omit<
ChipProps,
"label" | "col
